entry.title: MediaRecorder: Don't provide I420A if CanEncodeAlphaChannel() is false
entry.content:
A video encoder using media::VideoEncoder implementation in

MediaRecorder path checks I420A is provided only if

CanEncodeAlphaChannel() is true.

However, VideoTrackRecoder provides I420A to an encoder even if

CanEncodeAlphaChannel() returns false when ARGB is input to

VideoTrackRecorder. This works with its own h264 software encoder

because it converts ARGB and ABGR to I420A and then drops its alpha

channel. Although media::VideoEncoder for h264 also handles I420A

internally, it doesn't handle ARGB and ABGR. That's said, it depends

on a format whether the encoder can encode alpha channel.

It is more reasonable to convert a format and drop its alpha channel

in VideoTrackRecorder::VideoEncoder common code.



Bug: 1441395

entry.title: [CompositeClipPathAnimation] Allow worklet animations to avoid unnecessary frames
entry.content:
This change adds an additional function to PaintWorkletInput that allows for the paint worklet to avoid being invalidated if the value is not changed. This fixes an issue where composited animations with step timing functions would produce too many frames, creating a perf regression.



This is specifically done on the PaintWorkletInput level as opposed to the AnimatedPaintWorkletTracker level because composited clip path animations (and soon composited bgcolor animations) have their timing functions evaluated within the paint worklet.



This change only applies to clip path animations, however, this framework can be used for all derivations of PaintWorkletInput.

entry.title: identity.launchWebAuthFlow: center auth window for ODFS over Files app
entry.content:
Get the most recent Files app window and take its bounds, and use

these to launch the auth dialog so that it appears on top of and

centered on Files app (when launchWebAuthFlow() is called from ODFS).



This is to make auth calls from ODFS feel more associated with the

Files app window that triggered them. ODFS does not have its own UI

so we need to make this connection between the extension, Files app,

and launchWebAuthFlow(). We use a delegate for this to avoid overly

coupling the three.



This design leaves space for a lacros delegate later which can get

the necessary window bounds over crosapi. This is why the

GetOptionalWindowBounds() method is async even though it's not

strictly necessary yet.

entry.title: Apply RuntimeFeature attribute for methods in mojo cpp bindings
entry.content:
Enforces RuntimeFeature attributes on mojo methods.



```

feature kFeature {

const string name = "MyName";

const bool default_state = false;

};



interface Wolf {

[RuntimeFeature=kFeature]

EnableChaosWolf() => ();

};

```



In cpp runtime disabled methods cannot be called on remotes:



```

mojo::Remote remote;

...

remote->EnableChaosWolf(); // CHECK() failure if feature not enabled.

```



and receivers will not deserialize calls to disabled methods, causing

a normal validation failure.



Remotes are handled by adding a CHECK(feature) to the backing

generated proxy class. Receivers are handled by wrapping the

current params validation function with one that first tests

the associated feature then forwards to the normal validation

function.



Tests: mojo_unittests

entry.title: QRCodeGenerator::Generate: gracefully reject "impossible" min_version.
entry.content:
`QRCodeGenerator::Generate` accepts an optional `min_version` parameter

(which roughly corresponds to the size of the generated QR codes). Some

callers pass a hardcoded value here to guarantee a minimum size of the

generated QR code (e.g. so that painting a dino in the middle doesn't

interfere with error correction's ability to decode the QR code).

There are no callers where `min_version` is computed based on other

(potentially untrustworthy) input. Therefore, invalid `min_version`

values are "impossible".



Before this CL, "impossible" values of `min_version` would lead to Rust

panics (when validating the value in `qr_code_generator_ffi_glue.rs`) or

to a `CHECK` (when using `checked_cast<...>` on C++ side of the FFI

glue). This would lead to bug reports like https://crbug.com/1505660

and https://crbug.com/1505643 where fuzzing has produced an

"impossible" `min_version`. After this CL, "impossible" values are

handled more gracefully - returning an indication of "failure" instead

of crashing via a `panic` or `CHECK`.



Fixed: 1505643, 1505660

entry.title: Support for mojom RuntimeFeature on interfaces
entry.content:
This CL adds support for the `RuntimeFeature` attribute on mojom

interfaces in C++. See doc[0] for details.



```

module foo.mojom;



feature kTastyFeature {

const string name = "TastyFeature";

const bool default_state = false;

};



[RuntimeFeature=kTastyFeature]

interface GatedInterface {

// GatedInterface cannot be bound to a remote<> or receiver<>.

};



interface OtherInterface {

// Sending disabled interfaces will result in bad messages.

PassInterface(pending_remote? iface);

}

```



Developers should test the runtime feature to avoid binding or

calling a disabled interface:



```

remote remote = ...;



if (base::FeatureList::IsEnabled(kTastyFeature)) {

PendingRemote pending_guarded;

PendingReceiver pending_recv =

pending_guarded.InitWithNewEndpointAndPassReceiver();

auto impl = std::make_unique();

auto weak_ref =

MakeSelfOwnedReceiver(std::move(impl),

std::move(pending_recv));



remote->PassInterface(std::move(pending_guarded));

}

```



The annotation exists to allow

feature-flags to be enforced by the IPC system - but attempting to

use a disabled interface may lead to safe crashes in production

builds - it is up to developers to consult the exposed underlying

feature before attempting to use a disabled feature. DCHECKS in

test builds should validate this by crashing early.



In the example above - if kTastyFeature is not enabled and

the if() statement omitted:-



* pending_guarded & pending_recv will never bind.

* MakeSelfOwnedReceiver will return a null weak_ref.

* remote->PassInterface() will not serialize or deserialize the gated

interface.



Details



Feature tests happen via a templated function defined in

runtime_features.h and specialized in mojom-module.h files for

interfaces that define a RuntimeEnabled attribute. Interfaces

not guarded with a feature will work as before - checks for these are

emitted as constexpr templates so should not incur a runtime cost.



In release (non-DCHECK) builds mojo C++ bindings will (often

silently) not bind mojo message pipes to concrete receiver,

remote or SelfOwnedReceiver, and will refuse to serialize

pending disabled interfaces (resulting in a bad message).



In debug (DCHECK) builds mojo C++ bindings will crash if an

attempt is made to use a concrete remote or receiver for

an interface annotated with a disabled feature.



Compromised processes can still request or serialize disabled

interfaces, but the non-compromised end will consult its view

of the feature state and refuse to concretely bind such faked

requests.



Remote & Receiver sets gain Add() methods which return

an optional - these can replace uses of .Add() in contexts

where generic code might host feature guarded interfaces in future.



"casting" generic receivers via the .As() method

will return null receivers or DCHECK.



ServiceFactory will safely skip .Add()ing binders for disabled

interfaces.



RuntimeFeature is not yet implemented for methods, and non-C++

bindings are not yet aware of mojo-hosted features.



[0] https://docs.google.com/document/d/1kKFHu73SNwpBfPJzrVH2vLbpu9_1WuZhngFBqtJhwqw/edit?pli=1#heading=h.2s5rrpm5k56k



Tests: mojo_unittests --gtest_filter=FeatureBindingsTest.*
